For $\triangle ABC$ to be acute, each of its angles must be less than $90^\circ$.  This means that $\angle BAC$ must be less than $90^\circ$, $\angle ABC$ must be less than $90^\circ$, and $\angle ACB$ must be less than $90^\circ$.

Consider $\angle BAC$.  Let $C = (x,y)$.  Then $\overrightarrow{AC} = \begin{pmatrix} x - 2 \\ y - 2 \end{pmatrix}$ and $\overrightarrow{AB} = \begin{pmatrix} 5 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}$.  Since $\angle BAC$ is acute, the dot product of these two vectors must be positive:
\[\begin{pmatrix} x - 2 \\ y - 2 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 5 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix} = 5(x - 2) + 5(y - 2) > 0.\]This simplifies to $x + y > 4$.

Similarly, for $\angle ABC$ to be acute, we must have
\[\begin{pmatrix} 7 - x \\ 7 - y \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 5 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix} = 5(7 - x) + 5(7 - y) > 0.\]This simplifies to $x + y < 14$.

Finally, for $\angle ACB$ to be acute, we must have
\[\begin{pmatrix} x - 7 \\ y - 7 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 2 - x \\ 2 - y \end{pmatrix} = (x - 7)(2 - x) + (y - 7)(2 - y) > 0.\]This simplifies to $x^2 + y^2 - 9x - 9y + 14 < 0$.

Thus, the region $R$ is the intersection of the half-plane $x + y > 4$, the half-plane $x + y < 14$, and the interior of the circle $x^2 + y^2 - 9x - 9y + 14 = 0$.  The circle has center $\left( \frac{9}{2}, \frac{9}{2} \right)$ and radius $\frac{5}{2}$.

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, O;

A = (2,2);
B = (7,7);
O = (9/2,9/2);
C = intersectionpoint(arc(O,5/2,0,180),A--B);

draw((-1,0)--(10,0));
draw((0,-1)--(0,10));
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(Circle(O,5/2));
draw((4,0)--(0,4),dashed);
draw((0,10)--(10,4),dashed);

label("$A$", A, SW);
label("$B$", B, NE);
label("$C$", C, S);
label("$O$", O, N);
[/asy]

The region $R$ is the shaded triangle above.  Its base has length 5, and its height is 5, so its area is $\frac{1}{2} \cdot 5 \cdot 5 = \frac{25}{2}$.

